http://ptlm-linux1/twiki/bin/view/PADM/CanBusInformation EDCS-475530 CAN Bus Subsystem SFS EDCS-526779 CAN Bus Microcontroller (CBC) SDS EDCS-535163 Viking SW Chassis Management Software Design Specification
On the Viking platform, the CAN bus runs over the backplane and connects all the cards in the shelf. This includes both intelligent cards (cards that have a microprocessor) like Supervisor Card (SUP), Line Card (LC), and non-intelligent cards (cards that do not have a microprocessor) like Blank Card (BC), Fan Tray (FT) and Common Backplane Interface Connector (CBIC).
The term CAN bus Subsystem includes the CAN bus itself, the CAN bus microcontroller or controller (CBC for short), peripherals attached to and managed by the CBC and their associated functions.
The functions of the subsystem are: Provide a means to detect type of card by the SUP after card insertion. Monitor temperature and voltage locally on each card and take corrective and preventive measures if value is out of range. Provide a means to control power supply to each card from SUP. Monitor and control operation of fans on FT. Monitor and control operation of CBIC.
The CAN bus subsystem is a Microchip dsPIC33FJ128GP706TI/PT single chip microcontroller with integrated two separate CAN controllers. Additional internal peripherals include parallel I/O, 18 channel A/D converter, UART, SPI port, Timers, PWM modulators, and event capture registers. In the Viking system, supervisor cards, line cards, CBIC, Fan trays and blank cards will have CAN modules on the board, and communicate via two multi-drop and redundant CAN buses (A&B).
In addition, a small number of external components will be included in the CAN bus subsystem: CAN interface, manufacture EEPROM, LED matrix, temperature sensor and EDVT header.
